<h2>Welcome to my Health and Safety application </h2>

<p>This is a prototype application produced in conjunction with work placement in the DSP. The application is designed to allow users to:</p>

<ul>
    <li> Report Health and Safety issues</li>
    <li> Find their safety reps</li>
    <li> View details about reported incidents</li>
</ul>

<h2>User Manual</h2>
<h3>Find Details of Safety Representative</h3>
<p>The details of safety representatives are available on the safety contacts page. There are various routes available to access the page.</p>
<ul>
    <li> From the Home page: Press the ‘Find my Rep’ button</li>
    <li> From the navigation tab: Select  the ‘Safety Contacts’ tab</li>
</ul>

<p>The designated safety officers for any given building can be identified by selecting the appropriate ‘region’ from the dropdown list. After the region has been selected the list of buildings for that region will be available in the ‘Select building’ dropdown list. When the required fields have been selected, press ‘Search’ to display the requested information.</p>
<h3>View Incident Reports</h3>
<p>
    To view information about reported incidents the user must navigate to the ‘Incidents’ page. This page is accessible via various routes.
    <ul>
        <li> From the Home page: Press the ‘Find my Rep’ button</li>
        <li> From the navigation tab: Select  the ‘Safety Contacts’ tab</li>
    </ul>
    On the ‘Incidents’ page, the user can view a summary of incident data.
</p>
<h4>Pie Chart</h4>
<p>The pie chart displays the percentage breakdown of the types of incidents recorded in the database. This information is available to all users. By default the pie chart is hidden and can be viewed by clicking the ‘View Pie Chart’ button.</p>
<h4>Stacked Bar Chart</h4>
<p>The Stacked Bar Chart displays a breakdown of the types of incidents in each region recorded in the database. This information is available to all users. By default the Stacked Bar Chart is hidden and can be viewed by clicking the ‘View Pie Chart’ button.</p>
<h4>Incidents Table</h4>
<p>The incidents table is only viewable by Managers. The table displays details of incidents which are stored on the database.</p>
<h4>Sorting:</h4>
<p>By default the table is ordered by date, with the most recent incidents at the top of the table. This order can be reversed by clicking the header of the date column.</p>
<p>The table can also be ordered by the last name of the employee who reported the incident by clicking on the header of the last name column. This will order the data alphabetically and can be reversed by clicking the header of the column.</p>
<h4>Filtering:</h4>
<p>The table can be filtered by region and also by ‘type of incident’. To apply the filter, select your option from the dropdown list and press the ‘Search’ button.</p>
<h4>Export to Excel</h4>
The table can be exported to an excel document. This option is available by pressing the ‘Export to Excel’ button at the bottom of the table.
<h3>Report an Incident</h3>
<p>To Report an Incident navigate to the report incident page from the home page.</p>
<p>An incident can be classed as “an unplanned, undesired event that hinders completion of a task and may cause injury, illness, or property damage or some combination of all three in varying degrees from minor to catastrophic.” </p>
<p>In order to report an incident the user must navigate to the ‘Report Incident’ form. This form can be navigated to from the home page by pressing the ‘Report an Incident’ button. Alternatively the form can be accessed from the Incidents page by selecting the link – ‘Report an Incident’, which is located at the top of the page.</p>
<h4>Filling in the form</h4>
<p>The required fields are highlighted.</p>
<ul>
    <li>Type of Incident: The user must select a type of incident from the drop down list provided</li>
    <li>Select your region: Selecting the region will filter the list of buildings allowing the user to quickly distinguish the building where the incident occurred.</li>
    <li>Select your building: The building must be selected in order to record the location details in the database.</li>
    <li>Did incident involve a member of the public? The user can tick the check box if the incident involved a member of the public. This will present the user with an additional field requesting the details of the member of public. A member of public may be involved as a victim or perpetrator of the incident.</li>
    <li>Did incident occur whilst on a home visit? If the incident occurred whilst on a home visit the user can tick the check box.</li>
    <li>Brief Description: A brief description of what happened when the incident occurred can be entered here.</li>
    <li>Date of Incident: The user must enter a valid date on which the incident occurred.</li>
</ul>
<p> Upon completion of the form the user submits their report by pressing the ‘Send incident Report’ button.
The user is then presented with a confirmation box informing them that their Manager will be notified and requesting if they wish to confirm their submission.</p>
<ul>
    <li>Selecting ‘No’ will return the user to the form.</li>
    <li>Selecting ‘Confirm’ will record the incident to the database.</li>  
</ul>





